192
00:18:17,960 --> 00:18:19,120
Chief Li.

193
00:18:19,120 --> 00:18:21,260
Mr. Han, Mr. Yang.

194
00:18:21,260 --> 00:18:24,352
Our colleagues from Unit 158 are here.

195
00:18:25,401 --> 00:18:26,881
Hi.

196
00:18:26,881 --> 00:18:27,820
Hello.

197
00:18:27,820 --> 00:18:29,020
Allow me to introduce you,

198
00:18:29,020 --> 00:18:32,100
this is Chief Li, Head of the Technical Department in this center.

199
00:18:32,100 --> 00:18:35,660
These two are Mr. Yang and Mr. Han, also from the Technical Department.

200
00:18:35,660 --> 00:18:38,641
I'm Guan Zai from Unit 158, Satellite JX Chief Engineer.

201
00:18:38,641 --> 00:18:42,240
I'm Yu Tu from Unit 158, Satellite JX Engineer.

202
00:18:42,240 --> 00:18:45,000
Director Hu is in Taiyuan now with some business to attend to.

203
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:46,600
He'll be here tomorrow afternoon at the latest.

204
00:18:46,600 --> 00:18:48,180
Wonderful.

205
00:18:48,180 --> 00:18:49,480
- Thank you for your hard work, Xiao Lu. 
 - No worries.

206
00:18:49,480 --> 00:18:50,780
Have you prepared for their reception?

207
00:18:50,780 --> 00:18:52,700
The receptionists have done it. Don't worry.

208
00:18:52,700 --> 00:18:53,680
This is not urgent.

209
00:18:53,680 --> 00:18:58,460
Chief Li, I want to understand the latest situation of JX's orbit.

210
00:18:58,460 --> 00:19:03,320
Last night, after you transmitted the commands during the second and third rotation,

211
00:19:03,320 --> 00:19:05,121
was the downlink signal received?

212
00:19:05,121 --> 00:19:08,820
So when it entered our range, we sent the command straight away.

213
00:19:08,820 --> 00:19:11,840
However, we still haven't received the downlink signal.

214
00:19:11,840 --> 00:19:13,540
We switched to the backup and sent the command via fixed channels

215
00:19:13,540 --> 00:19:15,520
but there's no response.

216
00:19:19,720 --> 00:19:22,720
We brought along the related documents and drawings.

217
00:19:22,720 --> 00:19:25,451
Do you have any recent telemetry data of the satellite?

218
00:19:25,451 --> 00:19:26,940
It's all in our system.

219
00:19:26,940 --> 00:19:28,880
Let's figure out the problem, then.

220
00:19:28,880 --> 00:19:30,860
Once we find it, we can devise a solution.

221
00:19:30,860 --> 00:19:36,440
   

222
00:19:52,560 --> 00:19:56,040
   

223
00:20:01,380 --> 00:20:02,980
Are you okay?

224
00:20:04,547 --> 00:20:05,671
I'm getting old.

225
00:20:05,671 --> 00:20:08,116
One all-nighter and I'm dizzy already.

226
00:20:08,116 --> 00:20:13,017
Back then, a few hours of sleep for a few nights was no problem.

227
00:20:26,640 --> 00:20:28,453
I'll head to bed now.

228
00:20:35,799 --> 00:20:38,240
 I received another call from the ministry. 

229
00:20:38,240 --> 00:20:41,319
 The government invested a lot to launch this satellite. 

230
00:20:41,319 --> 00:20:44,880
 Now that it's not working, the ministry wants an explanation. 

231
00:20:44,880 --> 00:20:48,319
 Should we explore another options instead of focusing on the transponder? 

232
00:20:48,319 --> 00:20:50,380
 It could be the power supply. 

233
00:20:50,380 --> 00:20:54,399
 Besides, is it possible that its orbit has changed? 

234
00:20:54,399 --> 00:20:56,360
 The fixed channels might not be able to reach it. 

235
00:20:56,360 --> 00:20:59,559
 The power subsystem and the recent orbital data, I've read them all. 

236
00:20:59,559 --> 00:21:02,840
 The telemetry data is within the normal threshold. 

237
00:21:02,840 --> 00:21:04,600
 I've also checked the orbital data. 

238
00:21:04,600 --> 00:21:08,160
 It matches quite well with the predetermined orbit. 

239
00:21:08,955 --> 00:21:11,760
 However, Chief Guan and I designed the model. 

240
00:21:11,760 --> 00:21:18,459
 To reach a conclusion, we need to wait for the electrical and orbital engineers' input. 

241
